Either way, the way I look at the midterms, and I pray they're over soon, the Republicans win and the Democrats lose, no matter what. No matter what. And I'll tell you why. Because politics isn't personal to Republicans. So, if you do well, great. But I'm going to have dinner. But if you lose the house, well, that sucks. But I'm going to go have dinner. But now the Democrats -- let's say the Democrats win big, that's not going to be enough because he's still going to be in charge. That evil Trump is going to be there. So they're still going to be really angry. And if they lose, we saw what happened when they lost before, right? It was a countrywide tantrum.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: We should have had the scream.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, the scream. So, the thing is, because it's so intensely personal for Democrats, primarily liberals with politics, I don't think they're ever going to be pleased by the outcome. Where the Republicans, politics is just a facet in your life, it's one part of it. It's not your life. So, you know, you lose the house, you know, well, that's life. I'm going to go play with my kids. I don't have kids.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Juan, I'll just throw it over to you for whatever you want to say.

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Oh, well, I'm just amazed. It's the best economy ever, says Trump, and Jesse backs it up. Of course, just not true. And then you say it's not true and people are like, well, why are you picking on the president. Oh, stop picking.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Better than the Obamas.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But it's just unbelievable. And then, you know, the whole idea of this invading army is coming, oh, my gosh, you want to let them in. You know, it's just ridiculous. But, you know, to me, it's at a point where in this campaign you look at where the president is going. You look at what he's saying. So, today, West Virginia, also Indiana, he's going into red states and he's trying his best. I don't think he's gonna have any success with -- stopping Joe Manchin getting reelected. But when it comes to Joe Donnelly, the Democrat in a red state like Indiana, I think he may have some success because he can stir up the base. And that's all he's doing. So the whole attack on the caravan, everything that he says about the caravan being filled with disease and criminals, you know, it's just -- at some point you want to think, are these Republicans paying attention? Does it makes any.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Didn't Obama just say we're poisoning the air and water?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Let's get Morgan in here. Your thoughts about -- we have a week - - we're going into a weekend, it is also when you have to turn back the clocks, by the way.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's a clock.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Apparently -- I think that that is probably good news for Republicans, right? I'm kidding. I have no idea.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Tell me more, Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Trends tell us in the past.

utterances.speaker: MORGAN ORTAGUS, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Listen, I think it all comes down to undecided voters, which are largely independent, largely moderate. And something that I thought was interesting, and in this -- before the mail bomber happened, before the temple shooting happened, most of those independent voters are registering, saying that they felt unsure of putting the Democrats back in power because the message did worked, that they thought they were too extreme. Clearly, the events, you know, sort of stopped the momentum that they had. But they still sort of seem like, will I vote, will I not vote. What will happen? And we all know in all of these elections depends on who can motivate people to turn out. So, what I'm fascinated by -- I started going through, you know, state by state, we're all looking at the polling. I think it's going to be a really long election night. I'm looking forward to watching you, Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Juan will be there too.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: And Juan, too?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I won't.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: You can come to my party.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, great.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: As the wind blows, these races -- like, they're a plane apart, right? Like they're two planes apart, within the margin of error. We can see the senate looking exactly like it is. We can see the house looking similarly. Or we can see -- you know, we can see something go straight up or down for either party. I mean, it's going to be a fascinating evening. The one thing that I would say is to pay attention not just to the house and to the senate but these governor's races, 12 out of 13 Republican governors that are running for re-election are ahead. But 7 -- about 7 to 9 of them that are running in open seats, it's neck and neck. Talk about Georgia. Talk about Florida. I mean, these are the races where it could go into runoffs. We could be up all night.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I just want to pick up on something that Morgan just said. She's right. There's a lot of house races right now that a lot of prognosticators think, oh, you know what? Democrats are going to get them all. They're all within the margin of error. So there's no guarantee that this blue wave is going to happen. You can see a situation where Democrats pick up 20 seats in the house and come up a few seats short. There's no massive Democratic Party registration going on. There's no massive enthusiasm gap going on. There's no recession going on. There's just not a lot of indicators. Look at the generic congressional ballot. That's within single digits. The Democrats are down in the Connecticut governor's race.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: For good reason.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I mean, there's just a lot of things you scratch your head and you think, wait a second, the media was so wrong in 2016, could this be a flashback of what happened last time? There could be a silent majority out there that aren't talking to pollsters that could come out and then really shock the country.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I think that you're looking -- look at the ads, just so important right now. And the ads, both on the Republican and Democratic side.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: We have a chart. Can I just show that chart? I know we've got to go.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Dana loves her charts.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It's a great chart and I sent it to everyone this morning so that they could.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, 7 in the morning you get like 8 charts from Dana. Oh, great. That's what I want to look at when I wake up in the morning, stuff like this. Why don't you send me pictures of your dog instead?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, that can be arranged, of course. But this chart, if you go to Bloomberg, it tells you what ads are running in which regions of the country. So I thought that was actually very good. Didn't you think it was interesting?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I didn't look at it either.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I opened it and then I closed it.

utterances.utterance: Who sends charts before 9 AM?

utterances.utterance: Look, somebody has to get up early to work on the 2 o'clock.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And it was 10:30, thank you.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Dana, I must say, I valued it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I appreciated it. But I just want -- my point that I was going to make based on Dana's chart, by the way, would be that healthcare dominates on both sides, not this immigrations drivel, and not the phony ad that makes it out like Democrats want open borders. Again, it's like are Republicans suckers? What is going on here?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: What is going on?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Show that chart one more time.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Show the chart one more time.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know what that is?

utterances.utterance: Exactly.

utterances.utterance: Claire's not afraid to stand up against her own party.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: In Montana, Jon Tester, he's blasting Democrats for, quote, botching the Brett Kavanaugh confirmation hearing. And in Indiana, Joe Donnelly, backing increased border security. utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, Greg, guess what? Even in Montana -- Jon Tester, I should say, taking a swipe at Elizabeth Warren's DNA test.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: The mighty have fallen. And then, here we are, fast forward, not that long later, people don't want to be seen with him and, quite frankly, I think for good reason. I mean, at a minimum, the guy abused his power with a college intern. At the worst, he's been accused of some of the worst things that men can be accused of. So, I wouldn't want to be seen with him and I don't blame the Democrats. But on Claire McCaskill, the one thing that was interesting to me there is, you know, for all of the mantra of the Democrats about girl power, she was really quick to throw Elizabeth Warren, like, right under the bus.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I think she feels that Elizabeth Warren was critical of her on some votes, and so that's what she said. So, Jesse, what we see here is, right now, it's 51-49, Republicans in the senate. And you have Heidi Heitkamp trailing in North Dakota, close races in Indiana, Missouri. And then comes two interesting states, Arizona and Nevada. No Trump in either state, even though you would think immigration, which is his key message might play there, apparently, both Republican candidates want no part of Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, I don't know if that's true. But you're right, those races are dead even and -- they could go either way. And they're very interesting, two western states, a lot different than a lot of the other states in the country. But, on the Bill Clinton thing, I think there's three reasons for that. One, the Democratic Party has given up looking for white working-class voters. Bill Clinton was always great at speaking to those people. They don't really speak to those people as much as they used to, they've reprioritized to more identity politics. And millennials, I mean, they were born in the 90's, they barely remember Bill Clinton. And then you have the Me Too thing, if you bring him in you might catch too much heat. On the distancing, I think the distancing is disingenuous because the Democratic Party has been crazy for two years. And all of a sudden, a week before the election, now they're going to get the stomach to say, hey, guys, knock it off. I just don't buy it. And it kind of shows me, right now, the Republican Party is more unified than the Democratic Party. Looks like the Democrats are shooting within the tent a little bit, I don't know how that's going to play out, but it's an interesting indicator especially in these red swing states.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wow, this is a kinder, gentler, Jesse Watters. The Democrats have only been crazy for two years.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS

utterances.utterance: Well, I think she -- let's just take them one by one. I don't think that's going to wash with a lot of Republican voters. President Trump won that state by 19 points. You look at Jon Tester, I do think that's little bit different in Montana where you have Tester very close to the agriculture community, and they think he's done a good job for them. So he's trying to localize that race as much as possible. Not that Trump hasn't done all he can to help Rosendale and the Republicans still could win there. That was a nail biter. Donnelly, though, he does -- he's one of the only ones that can say he has voted with President Trump and he did so on immigration. So this last bit of President Trump, closing argument on immigration, might not play as much in Indiana because Donnelly, actually, has a voting record that says that. The other thing is each of these three states President Trump's approval rating is above 50 percent. That's a big deal for him because if you think back -- like in 2002, the first Bush mid-term, I think President Bush's approval rating was sky high, we were at war, after 9/11. But in 2006, when he lost the majorities his approval rating was 37 percent. It makes a big difference especially in these tight races. So President Trump has done them a favor, by getting his approval rating up to where it is.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Can we go to that chart?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I just want to say for the record that in the commercial break Jesse Watters said my charts was very helpful.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I did.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Let me just say that what strikes me is that in these big states, these red states where Democrats are struggling, they're close races. And you would think that right now, since they're red states, that Republicans are dominating. Not.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That's why you want to tune in to get to Fox News voter analysis on Tuesday.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: There you go.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Twenty percent more charts.

utterances.utterance: All right. Is Michael Avenatti getting ready to take on Trump with a 2020 run? Oh, my goodness, could it be? See his new political ad, next.

utterances.utterance: Michael Avenatti, again, fueling speculation about his presidential ambition. The anti-Trump lawyer urging people in his first ad -- first political ad to get out and vote. Watch this.

utterances.utterance: We will not be silent.

utterances.utterance: And we will fight.

utterances.utterance: Join us.

utterances.utterance: Our constitution says we the people. Not me, the president. Stand up. Join the fight club. Use your vote as your voice on November 6.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: So, Greg, I saw it, the first rule of Fight Club was not to talk about it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, good point. He actually chose actors and actresses as appealing as he is. Everybody is just scowling. By the way, this guy has more baggage than JFK, and I'm talking about the airport, Dana.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Having said that, so did Donald Trump. He had baggage. But the difference is Avenatti is all baggage and no ticket. His resume is thinner than his hair. And he -- but I want him, I encourage him to go because it'll be incredibly entertaining to see him up on the dais with actual other candidates and see how that goes.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Juan, I think that Greg sounds a lot like the Democrats sounded whenever President Trump announced.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: What do you think?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, I was thinking a lot of what Greg was saying, that, you know, Donald Trump, what was his resume, what were his credentials?

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Come on, he's more qualified than Avenatti.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Let me finish my point that I think -- and so I was reading about this and somebody said, in fact, Donald Trump is better known than Avenatti. But if you think about The Apprentice, all the years he was on TV, plus, the fact that people associate Donald Trump with money, with wealth, that it gave him more of a standing in the public mind. Avenatti doesn't have that. But in terms of actual resume, I don't know? You think that Donald Trump is highly qualified to be President of the United States?

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Well, we're not going to get into that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He is.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But he is president, but he's not qualified. That's the problem.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Well, OK, I'm not going to go there. So, Dana, tell me -- you know, when the Democrats clearly, I think, want someone who's going to pick a fight with Trump, take on a fight with him, but doesn't Avenatti go a little-bit too far in terms of -- I don't think that mainstream voters or independent voters -- they might want.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Another difference between Avenatti and President Trump, is that President Trump has a great sense of humor and an impeccable comedic timing, because even Democrats will laugh. I think that Democrats right now are happy to let Avenatti be out in front, right? Let him be taking all those slings and arrows and getting the C-block on The Five. He'll be the one being made fun out, while they figure out -- OK, out of the 35 of us who all want to run for president, how are we going to blaze a trail.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Jesse, what do you think -- I mean, if he did get the nomination, what do you think, like, the mainstream news media anchors -- can you just envision that debate? utterances.utterance: Well, it won't happen. But he is going to be a player at the debates for the Democrats. utterances.utterance: Well, there is some truth to this. Christmas music is so bad that if there was no such thing as Christmas, no one would play this music again. Right. utterances.utterance: There's no study. They refer to this other stuff about stress and it was just -- thank you, that's the chart.

utterances.utterance: I will.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Greg and I agree?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Alec Baldwin brought you guys together. Imagine that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Greg's defense tag team.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Ok.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, from what I understand, he was parallel parking, some guy comes right in behind him, to take the space. That is totally crazy. I don't even think it was an illegal immigrant.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know why this upsets you because you don't like people who cut in line. You like process. You like order. You like enforcement.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I do. But I'll tell you what --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Build the wall -- Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Things were so crazy because I've been in that situation --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I have, too.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- where you're parallel parking and they know, they just decide "screw you".

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, yes, yes. Because they don't think you're going to fight back.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, you've never had this problem because you don't drive, right -- Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Not in New York. I've never driven in New York. I do think my favorite part of the day was when President Trump out front of Marine One, he can barely hear anything as a reporter is shouting questions. And somebody said Alec Baldwin was just arrested. He's like who? Alec Baldwin. For what. In New York for punching somebody. And he said I wish him the best of luck. He was quite nice.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: But the possibility is he didn't hear who it was. I wish him the best of luck? It was like, it could have been --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I was surprised the media didn't --

utterances.speaker: GUFELD
utterances.utterance: Where do you park your big wheel?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: In my tiny closet.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, look who's talking. Morgan -- what do you think? I'm surprised the media didn't blame Donald Trump for inciting the violence.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: I want to take this opportunity to complain about bikers in New York.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Ok.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Because I don't even care about people parallel parking, I don't drive either. I hate driving. But bikers in New York are the worst. They're the ones who don't pay attention. So if you're going to punch anyone, punch a biker.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Don't say that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: We condemn violence.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Do not -- do not punch bikers.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: My husband is going to agree with you.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Figuratively, figuratively.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: All right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Ok. And finally, is a hot dog a sandwich? With National Sandwich Day coming up, Oscar Mayer reignited the food fight on Twitter proclaiming that a hot dog is, in fact, a sandwich and boldly urging those who disagreed to leave them angry messages on a hotline. I don't know, guys, you know technically it's bread with meat in the middle. But I would not consider a hot dog a sandwich.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Why would you want to dilute your marketing advantage by being unique? Like be a hot dog -- be a sandwich, just be a hot dog.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Because this is exactly the message that the Democrats should be running on. Because this could unite a country beyond politics. A hot dog is a hot dog -- if a hot dog is a sandwich, then a corn dog is a lollipop. Because they're confusing structure with substance which happens a lot.

utterances.speaker: MORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: I'm taking the opposite position, I think it's a sandwich and I also think a taco is a sandwich.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Really.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: What? A taco is a taco.

utterances.speaker: MORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: It's carbs. It's -- it's all the same -- you can eat with it your hands.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think that's cultural appropriation. A taco is a taco.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. And I know a lot about that. Â The Mexican people will be very upset by that. They like the taco and they don't want it to be associated with North American tradition.

utterances.speaker: MORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Did you interview people about this today?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. I've been down the streets all day about this.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: A British psychologist did a study.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right. Is there a chart on that -- Dana? Do you have anything on that?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I can get you one by tomorrow at 7:00 a.m.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Ok. All right. There it is. There it is. The yellow is the mustard.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You're being hazed by the producers.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know what I think about this?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What's that -- Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: This is an advertising scheme. That's all it is.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. And you know what -- now we're eating a hot dog for work --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Mission accomplished.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- I love this segment. Stay right there -- fan mail Friday with Greg, up next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: More massage music for a friction-free Friday as I like to call it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Disgusting.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: "Fan Mail Friday", what's that -- it was about how we aren't fighting on Friday.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Ok.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Ok. This is from Debbie O. This is a great question for Facebook. "If we were all forced to wear a warning label what would yours say?"

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Do not consume while operating heavy machinery.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That would be yours?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That would be mine.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Very good.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Who is going to consume you?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't know -- view me, watch me, whatever you call it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What about you -- Juan?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I guess on TV arguing every day, so leave him alone.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: A little bit of warning -- do not approach when quiet.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, my God.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Morgan?

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: I don't know. Like hot to the touch.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, you're like a stove.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Something like that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, something like that. Dana.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I would say do not eat with your mouth open around her.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Wow, that's an interesting one.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Are you saying that because I was eating the hot dog?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No, I didn't notice.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That was disgusting -- Morgan. Mine would be choking hazard because I'm small.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, so cute.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. Anyway. Greg K., nice name, "If you had to assign each other to a brand of something to be the face of, what would each of yours be? It's kind of a complicated question.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: So we have to pick somebody else and say they would be the face for blank. I would say Jesse would be the face of Hawaii because his hair is like a big tidal wave.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Thank you very much.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think that's a compliment.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Thank you very much. I hope so.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You're like -- you're like old McGarrett.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't know who that is.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The original McGarrett from "Hawaii 5-0".

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That was before my time.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Jack Lord -- everybody. Dana.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: I have one -- oh sorry.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Ok.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: So worked at is Estee Lauder in college --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Must be nice.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: -- you would be a great -- Dana, you'd be a great face of Estee Lauder.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, my goodness -- that's a huge compliment.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Ok.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Now, you have to do the same thing to her.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think that I would -- you know what I would do? Because I think this is important and what she does is impressive -- why don't you make her the face of recruiting for the navy for women across the country.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well done.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You could probably create a chart-for-her. Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I like Roger Starback (ph) better than you for the --

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Well, thanks.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Let's see. So let me see -- let's see. my friends around here at this table are nutty, so maybe like peanut butter? You've got to be the face of Skippy.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, I would make you the face of the resistance -- Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Gladly. Gladly.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You're out of control.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Are you going to make Greg the face of something?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I could be the face of troubled geniuses. I don't know what that is.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Or Tums.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Or Tums. But you know what -- this question is about me.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, ok.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: There -- you want to read it?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Sure.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Tina R.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: This question from Tina R. is, "My teenage daughter wants to be the next Greg Gutfeld. What advice would you give?"

utterances.speaker: MORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: I think you have to answer that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: How about snarky and cynical? Practice, practice, practice.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think you have to learn a lot about language. You've got to love the English language and words. And you've got to learn how to write, you have to read a lot, and you have to be willing to, you know, play with words a little bit.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I was hoping the answers would be more insulting -- Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. I would drink a bottle of wine every night. I would wake up very cranky --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Teenager --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- and I would yell at the producers all day long.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Exactly.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You're right on track.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Exactly. That's 90 percent of the job. Morgan.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And all caps on e-mails.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What do you say.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: I have no answer how to answer this one. Don't be like Greg -- be you.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Very nicely done.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I said. you have to practice snarky. Snarky -- you've got to have that attitude.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I would say if you want to be -- if my teenage daughter wants to be the next Greg Gutfeld, you have to go with the hormone treatment. All right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. Literally.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: How much time I got? This is, all right, this is from Mlappin1. "What's the strangest family tradition in your family?" A little redundant there, Mlappin1. You could have said just what's the strangest family tradition. That was a really stupid --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But he said "in your family". So he wants you to be very specific.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, you know, we kind of understood that-- Dana. You have a lot of weird family traditions.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I don't. I can't think of a single thing to put --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, no, no, no. You grew up on a farm.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But that's not a tradition. I mean, I can't --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. But there are certain things you do on a farm that a lot of people don't know -- secret things.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Like milking cows and things like that? Breaking ice? I can't think of a single family tradition. Mom, I'm so sorry, I'm sure there are some. But then strange? I don't have any. Sorry. Sorry.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So when we were driving in car trips as a young kid we would drive underneath if the train was going over us when we were doing the underpass, everybody would take their hands and put their hands on the top of the celling of the car in case the train crashed through and killed our car.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes, everybody did that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Did you guys do that, too? You stole my tradition.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We never had that tradition.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, I wouldn't want to drive with you anywhere for a long car ride.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Wait until we take our bus trip this summer.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Juan -- any family traditions?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, you know, I mean obviously things like New Year's Day, when my original family, the one I was born into, they would do like black- eyed peas and oranges and things like that. But lately so my new nuclear family, we do a thing going on vacation, we all dress in the same sweat suit.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That's very strange.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You have to show a picture of that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That is strange.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: We ought to see that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's strange. Morgan.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: I don't know that we have anything -- we do have a tradition growing up that my father liked to make grits and eggs and biscuits -- we're from the south. And so we did it at dinner, though -- not for breakfast. We'd have breakfast for dinner.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I love that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Breakfast for dinner.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: We only got breakfast for dinner if my dad was traveling on business because he hated breakfast for dinner.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: We only had breakfast for dinner when mom and dad were drunk. They'd be like -- you know what, why don't you guys have some breakfast, here some cereal. All right.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: I don't believe that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: All right. "One More Thing" is up next.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Hi, Mom.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It's time now for "One More Thing". And we have a great one planned -- Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's right. So ever since we went to Texas we've just been inundated with people sending us the best barbecue from all over the country. Now, courtesy of Mommy and Big Daddy over he -- he went to Morgan's Brooklyn Barbecue. It's right off of Flatbush Avenue, right next to the Barclays Center. Chef Cenobio hooked us up with some serious brisket that's been cooked for 14 hours. We've got some chicken here. Greg is working on a rib. I just want to say thank you, guys so much. This looks absolutely fantastic. Speaking of fantastic, "WATTERS' WORLD" 8:00 p.m. Saturday. We're going to be live. So check that out -- a special election edition. Don't miss it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Who is on?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, the usual cast. The Mooch.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Congressman Sean Duffy.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, we've got Duffy. We've got Sarah Carter who's doing a caravan expose -- Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Is she in the caravan?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: She's been down there. She's going to be reporting just the facts.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Greg -- don't you want the macaroni and cheese?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No. Because I'm on -- I've had rib. I have the brisket.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Come on. You had some in Texas.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'll have the mac and cheese.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right. Juan -- go for it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right. So you know, not all politics is about money, polling, backslapping, baby kissing. Even in the midst of the toughest campaign season, you can just have fun. Take a look -- 78-year-old Congressman John Lewis -- Lewis was at a campaign event for Georgia gubernatorial candidate Stacey Abrams. As he was waiting for Abrams and Oprah Winfrey, Lewis began dancing to Pharell Williams' song, "Happy". The video of the Congressman, a civil rights icon, has gone viral.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No. Not viral.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Nearly half a million people, Gregory, have viewed it. And that was as of this morning. So it's a lot of fun.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Theresa May needs to take some lessons from him.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You like his dancing better than Theresa May?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: A lot better.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: That was so awful.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Everyone agrees.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Is that right?

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: I know.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Greg -- before you take another bite, you want to do your one more thing?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, sure. All right. Saturday special live edition of "THE GREG GUTFELD SHOW" 10:00. I've got Charlie Hurt. I've got Tom Shillue. I've got Kat Timpf. Tyrus. If you're going to watch Jesse's show -- stick around and watch my show. It's live. It's going to be very exciting. Now it's time for something special. Greg's "what the heck is that?" Now, I often look for a tape of mysterious animals and I think I outdid myself. I want you to take a look at this and all of you have to guess what this might be.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: What that little varmint is?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. Well, you're halfway there. It is a varmint.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Is at a rabbit?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's not a rabbit.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Is it a wolverine?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, it's not a wolverine.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: A field mouse.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: A rat.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: A muskrat.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: By the way, this video goes on for 30 minutes so we're going to go -- we're going to bleed into "SPECIAL REPORT". Sorry -- Bret.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I have no idea.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Bret right now is sitting at his desk going like, what the hell is going on over there? That is a chinchilla.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They make coats (ph) out of those things.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Way to scare the kids. They make coats out of them.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: All right. I will go next. So I haven't talked about this in a while. You know, I have the group, Minute Mentoring. This is where I started this group where you do -- it's like speed dating but mentoring for young professional women. Well, we have a newsletter that we restarted. And we're going to put it out every other week. It is something you've got to see. It's called selfie Friday. We have the word of the week. We have all sorts of mentoring tips for you there and also some fun articles. You can sign up for the page to receive next week's edition at Facebook.com/DanaPerino. That's Facebook.com/DanaPerino. Join us there, it's fabulous.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know what's great about Minute Mentoring. It's so brilliant because if it turns out you don't like the person you've got 55 seconds, 50 seconds to get them out of your office.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I believe it's 10 minutes but you have to be super efficient but the newsletter is great and I hope you sign up for it at that page.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Have you ever mentored anybody, honestly?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I kind of do street mentoring.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: What does that mean. If I see somebody in the street that needs some advice, I'll go over and talk to them.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Is that right. You are a friend to the homeless.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Remember that one guy that used to be the college associate?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The guy who always wore a suit every day?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right. Let's move on.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's the opposite of what you should tell them.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Ok. Morgan.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: Thank you. So I found my next vacation destination. There's a hotel in the Maldives called "The Maraca". It is the first underwater hotel villa. We've got some pictures of it here.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, no.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: It is located under the sea --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No way. No, thank you.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: -- yes, 16 feet below -- well, I'm a diver. So I would like to do this -- 16 feet below sea level in the middle of the Indian Ocean. It's in the Maldives.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Wow.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: And so you could see glass walls. The hotel room is essentially an aquarium which I think it is amazing. It sleeps nine guests. It comes with a gym, private security detail, a butler and two jet skis.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Aren't you worried?

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
utterances.utterance: The only problem --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I don't think it's real.

utterances.speaker: ORTAGUS
